    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.13.24"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">24</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">GEORGE SYLVESTER VIERECK
                        <lb/>
                    627 WEST 113TH ST. NEW YORK</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>October 3, 1928.</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. George<sic>John</sic> <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>c/o Post Dispatch</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>St. Louis, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I read with great interest your review of <hi rend="caps">MY FIRST TWO THOUSAND YEARS</hi>. I marvel at your memory for some of my youthful epigrams. They must have been better than I thought if they impressed you and so deeply that you remember them after all these years.</p>
                
                <p>It may interest you that I am publishing two other books this season. One is the autobiography of the Empress Hermine entitled <hi rend="caps">AN EMPRESS IN EXILE</hi>, written in collaboration with the Empress and published by Sears and Company. The other is a story of America's participation in the war, entitled <hi rend="caps">AS THEY SAW US</hi>, in which I cooperated with Marshal Foch, General Ludendorff, three French and three German generals, published by Doubleday, Doran and Company.</p>
                
                <p>I am out of polics and back in literature. Judging by the reception which <hi rend="caps">MY FIRST TWO THOUSAND YEARS</hi> has received, it seems to me that I could not have afforded to wait at the roadside much longer. All the reviews which I have seen so far have been sympathetic, but most of the reviewers belong to a generation that knows not Joseph! You are the only one whose memory embraces the past. Are we then both so ancient? I shall be forty-four before the end of the year. How old are you?</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Faithfully yours,</salute>
                
                    <signed>George Sylvester Viereck</signed>
                
                    <note>GSV:GD</note>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>The autobiography of the Empress Hermine was also published serially in the Saturday Evening Post.</p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
